Bunzl, HSBC, Home Retail Group, Elan: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 
2011-04-20T06:36:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-20/home-retail-virgin-media-u-k-irish-equity-market-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and
Irish markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last market close.  Futures on the benchmark  FTSE 100 Index (UKX)  expiring in June
rallied 1 percent to 5,913 at 7:35 a.m. in  London . Yesterday,
the FTSE 100 rose 26.79 points, or 0.5 percent, to 5,896.87. The
 FTSE All-Share Index (ASX)  gained 0.5 percent while Ireland’s ISEQ
Index advanced 0.8 percent.  Bunzl Plc (BNZL)  : The company said group revenue rose 12
percent in the first quarter at constant exchange rates as a
result of acquisitions and additional trading days. The shares
climbed 0.2 percent to 714.5 pence.  Elan Corp. (ELN ID): The Irish drugmaker said first-quarter
sales rose to $313 million, compared with $310.5 million in the
same period a year earlier. The stock jumped 4.7 percent to 5.78
euros.  Home Retail Group Plc (HOME)  : The owner of Argos catalog
stores said full-year benchmark pretax profit fell 13 percent to
254 million pounds ($415 million). That compares with the 250.4
million-pound average estimate of 21 analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg. The retailer maintained the dividend for the year at
14.7 pence a share. The stock dropped 3.2 percent to 209.3
pence.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  :  Europe ’s largest bank was
upgraded to “overweight” from “equal weight” at Morgan
Stanley.  “We believe that performance could improve meaningfully
from 2010, driven by Asia, cost control, lower impairments, and
by leveraging its balance sheet and funding advantage to
increase loan growth and gain share,” London-based analyst
Steven Hayne wrote in a report dated yesterday.  The shares lost 0.5 percent to 640.6 pence.  Virgin Media Inc. (VMED)  : The U.K.’s second-largest pay-
television company said first-quarter operating profit climbed
7.6 percent as it shifted customers toward higher-speed
broadband products. The shares gained 2.2 percent to 1,707
pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
